"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92523","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-20","<p>The intention of the Feed-in-Tariffs (FITs) policy change announced on 2 October 2014 is to help ensure that building mounted installations - which can help to reduce energy bills, deliver a reduction in pressure on the electricity grid, build on the UK supply chain, result in greater on-site use and support additional jobs – do not suffer from tariff degressions as a result of ground-mounted installations. It is one of a package of measures which the Government is implementing with the aim of ensuring the building mounted sector is well placed to deploy, whilst at the same challenged to innovate and bringing down costs. Estimates of the impact on deployment of 50kW and over rooftop solar installations were set out in the accompanying Impact Assessment (see Table 7):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360306/FITs_solar_IA_MASTER.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360306/FITs_solar_IA_MASTER.pdf</a>.</p><p>This showed that the impact on cumulative deployment to 2020/21 is estimated to range from -150MW to +90MW.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92523/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-20T15:19:33.4773284Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92523/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92523/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-10","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate he has made of likely changes in the number of 50kW and over rooftop solar installations deployed in each year from 2015-16 to 2020-21 as a result of changes to feed-in tariffs announced by his Department on 2 October 2014.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","209291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92524","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-14","<p>The Bioenergy Emissions and Counterfactual model can be used by developers and generators to ensure that they are sourcing biomass responsibly. However, the model does not in itself propose specific regulatory measures.</p><p>The Department continues to work on the analysis necessary in order to consider the appropriateness and potential design of any such measures. The Contracts for Difference include flexibility to amend the sustainability criteria in the future, should the Department’s further policy work and analysis show that this is needed.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92524/answer",,,,,,"2014-11-14T12:12:09.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92524/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92524/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-10","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when the conclusions of the Biomass Emissions and Counterfactual report will be included in Government sustainability standards for bioenergy.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","209290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92525","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-20","<p>The amount that deploys under Contracts for Difference (CfDs) will depend on the strike price at which CfDs are awarded (the auction clearing price), as well as the mix of technologies amongst the successful bidders. The allocation round is currently underway for CfDs and DECC is not in a position to predict the outcome of the CfD auctions.</p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92525/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-20T15:20:17.9052161Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92525/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92525/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-10","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate he has made of the amount of large-scale solar PV that will be deployed in 2015-16 under Contracts for Difference; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","209293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92526","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-15","<p>Our recent consultation confirmed our policy that solar PV for projects of 5MW and below will continue. We continue to monitor the Renewables Obligation solar PV deployment pipeline for projects of 5MW and below. As indicated in our recent government response to the consultation on changes to financial support for solar PV<sup>1</sup>, if this monitoring indicates that deployment is growing more rapidly than can be afforded, we will consider taking measures to protect the Levy Control Framework. Any such proposals would require further consultation.</p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360280/Government_response_RO-FIT_changes_to_Solar_PV_-_FINAL_2014-10-02.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360280/Government_response_RO-FIT_changes_to_Solar_PV_-_FINAL_2014-10-02.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92526/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-15T13:55:33.4773397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92526/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92526/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-10","Solar Power: Renewables Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the Renewables Obligation for sub-5mW solar will be reviewed or consulted on before May 2015.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","209292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92527","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-10-22","<p>A table, providing information on the number of claims associated with mine shafts and adits over the last 10 years, along with information on the expenditure incurred in their treatment, will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p><p>The Coal Authority do not differentiate between private and local authority so I am unable to provide the data split as requested.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92527/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-22T15:47:15.640619Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92527/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92527/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-10","Mining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what amount has been paid in compensation or remediation for subsidence related to mineshafts and shaft collapse on (a) private and (b) local authority land in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Joan Walley","Stoke-on-Trent North","Joan Walley","209914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92528","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Research into alternative methods for dealing with the risk of M. bovis from badgers (e.g. sett-based culling methods and non-lethal methods) is underway. This includes investigations into the potential use of gas as a sett-based means of humane culling.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These tests for the potential use of carbon monoxide will not involve badgers.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92528/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T11:46:40.5481299Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92528/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92528/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has conducted trials in gassing of badger sets to control the spread of tuberculosis in cattle.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","209823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92529","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>As a result of discussions facilitated by the European Commission, there is now a consensus amongst interested Member States to significantly reduce targeting of bass across all sectors exploiting that stock. The Commission has also requested advice from the North Sea, North Western Waters and South West Waters Advisory Councils on the appropriate short term measures to apply in 2015, and the development of a long term management plan. We expect EU bass management proposals to be published before the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK Government will continue to push for effective EU-wide conservation measures that will ensure the stock recovers and becomes sustainable by working with the Commission and interested Member States. We will consider the need for any further domestic management of bass in the light of these European discussions.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92529/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T10:48:05.9552219Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92529/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92529/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","White Fish: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of progress made by the European Commission on steps to sustainably manage bass stocks using technical conservation measures; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","209904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92530","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Between 2009 and 2013 there have been 12 contraventions under sections of the Water Industry Act 1991 in England, with one of these occurring in the North West. There were no contraventions in the Lancashire area.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92530/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T10:45:47.4333453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92530/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92530/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Water Industry Act 1991","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many contraventions of the Water Industry Act 1991 there have been in (a) England, (b) the North West and (c) Lancashire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","209943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92531","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-27","<p>Answers to Parliamentary Questions are drafted by staff across the Department. Whilst core Defra has no direct employees paid less than the London Living Wage there are a small number of temporary staff from employment agencies who are paid less than the London Living Wage. Senior Civil Servants are responsible for providing final advice and draft responses to Ministers.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92531/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-27T16:54:09.5882156Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92531/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92531/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff of her Department or its contractors who are responsible for drafting responses to Parliamentary Questions are paid below the rate of the London living wage.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","209931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92532","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>The Clean Air Act includes fines for various offences to be enforced by local authorities through the magistrate courts. It does not provide for enforcement on local authorities. As the regulators, records of these should be held by local authorities. There is no requirement in the Act for local authorities to notify Defra of fines levied. Therefore, the department does not hold data for offences recorded as issued by local authorities for companies or private individuals.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92532/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T10:45:18.1511875Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92532/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92532/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Clean Air Act 1993","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, to which local authorities penalties have been issued for breaches of the Clean Air Act 1993 since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Laura Sandys","South Thanet","Laura Sandys","209923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92533","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Defra issued an air pollution alert to the public on 18 July this year due to levels of ozone measured at Sibton (189µgm<sup>3</sup>) and St Osyth (185µgm<sup>3</sup>) in Eastern England. The alert was issued when hourly measurements exceeded the ozone public information threshold of 180 µg/m<sup>3</sup> (micrograms per metre cubed) as defined in the Air Quality Directive 2008/50/EC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The alert was issued on Defra’s UK_Air website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/latest/alerts" target="_blank">http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/latest/alerts</a>, and air quality Twitter feed @defraUKAir, giving details of the locations and measurements, as well as relevant health advice. Members of the public can also receive air quality information such as alerts by signing up to email bulletins at <a href="http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/subscribe" target="_blank">http://uk-air.defra.gov.uk/subscribe</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra works closely with Public Health England to ensure information and health advice is provided to the public when pollution levels are elevated.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92533/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T11:08:18.5958495Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92533/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92533/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Ozone: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how and to whom the pollution alert on ozone in Eastern England was distributed on 18 July 2014.","false","Biography information for Laura Sandys","South Thanet","Laura Sandys","209924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92534","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>There are currently no UK vessels fishing under the new protocol to the EU-Morocco Fisheries Partnership Agreement. Decisions on any quota allocation and licensing would be made by UK authorities under the existing regulatory regime.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92534/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T10:50:35.664804Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92534/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92534/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Western Sahara","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether any UK trawlers are fishing in the waters of Western Sahara under the new protocol to the EU-Morocco Fisheries Partnership Agreement; and what her policy is on utilising the UK allocation under that agreement.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","209940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92535","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>The Government will be laying draft regulations shortly to make it compulsory for all dogs in England to be microchipped from 2016. The regulations will be subject to the affirmative procedure before coming into force. Defra is working with all relevant stakeholders to communicate the requirement to dog breeders and owners beforehand.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92535/answer",,,,,"209939","2014-10-17T10:49:45.7552929Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92535/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92535/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Dogs: Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the statement of 6 February 2013, Official Report, column 15WS, on irresponsible dog ownership, when she intends to bring forward legislative proposals on implementation of compulsory microchipping in England.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","209972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92536","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>The power to designate smoke control areas under Part 3 of the Clean Air Act 1993 lies with local authorities as the regulators. Under the Act local authorities are required to publish details of the areas created in the London Gazette and their local newspapers prior to creating the associated smoke control orders. Therefore, the definitive lists of designated areas are held by individual local authorities.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92536/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T10:48:48.6926884Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92536/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92536/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Smoke and Chimney Gases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, which smoke control areas are currently designated in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Laura Sandys","South Thanet","Laura Sandys","209922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92537","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>The Government will be laying draft regulations shortly to make it compulsory for all dogs in England to be microchipped from 2016. The regulations will be subject to the affirmative procedure before coming into force. Defra is working with all relevant stakeholders to communicate the requirement to dog breeders and owners beforehand.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92537/answer",,,,,"209972","2014-10-17T10:49:45.8959548Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92537/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92537/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Dogs: Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the statement of 6 February 2013, Official Report, column 15WS, on irresponsible dog ownership, what the timetable is for implementing compulsory microchipping of dogs in England by 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","209939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92538","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Defra has not directly commissioned research on the levels of resistance of crops to protective chemicals sprayed on them by farmers because the Health and Safety Executive carries out an assessment of the impact of pesticide products on target and non-target plants. We can be confident in this work because under the European Union regulatory regime for pesticides, the Health and Safety Executive, as the UK pesticides regulator, assesses and authorises pesticide products for specific uses following comprehensive evaluations of detailed applications for authorisation from pesticide manufacturers.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92538/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T13:52:38.5947512Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92538/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92538/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Pesticides","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what research her Department has (a) commissioned and (b) assessed on levels of resistance of crops to protective chemicals sprayed on them by farmers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","209860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92539","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Revenue spend</p><p> </p><p>The Dartford area covers three flood risk management systems and one major structure - the Dartford Creek Barrier.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Spend for last 12 months (£K)</p></td><td><p>Remaining budget for 2014/15 (£K)</p></td><td><p>Funding needs identified for 2015/16 (£K) (not yet approved)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Thames</p></td><td><p>71.1</p></td><td><p>59.7</p></td><td><p>80.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dartford</p></td><td><p>4.4</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>23.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South Darent</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>17.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dartford Creek Barrier</p></td><td><p>135.0</p></td><td><p>65.0</p></td><td><p>135.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Capital spend</p><p> </p><p>In the next 12 months we will carry out an initial assessment to assess flood risk in Dartford town centre from the fluvial River Darent at a cost of approximately £50K.</p><p> </p><p>Capital expenditure on the Dartford Creek Barrier has been as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Spend for last 12 months (£K)</p></td><td><p>Remaining budget for 2014/15 (£K)</p></td><td><p>Funding needs identified for 2015/16 (£K) (not yet approved)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dartford Creek Barrier</p></td><td><p>65.0</p></td><td><p>120.0</p></td><td><p>200.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92539/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T11:10:55.2086666Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92539/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92539/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Floods: Dartford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much has been spent on flood defences in Dartford in the last 12 months; and what future such spending is planned in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","209884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92540","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-16","<p>Core Defra operates a dual numbering system for all 0845 prefix telephone lines with the prefix 03 used as the primary number. 0845 prefix numbers have been retained to allow callers a choice based on their call package arrangements. There is no timetable to phase out the 0845 prefixed numbers but a review of the dual numbering policy will conclude in November.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92540/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-16T14:33:37.3094115Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92540/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92540/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what timetable is in place for the phase-out of her Department's telephone lines with the prefix (a) 0845, (b) 0844 and (c) 0843.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","209954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92541","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Dairy UK wrote to the Secretary of State recently requesting a meeting to further discuss the global dairy market situation and its impacts on domestic farmgate milk prices. The Secretary of State and I will be meeting Dairy UK and milk processors later this month.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I have also discussed this issue with farmers and their representatives and discussed the issue with Alex Ferguson ahead of publication of his review into the voluntary dairy supply chain code.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra has received a small number of letters from farmers and others on the subject of milk prices.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92541/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T11:13:08.7251492Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92541/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92541/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Milk: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent representations she has received on changes in the price of milk and its effect on milk producers.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","209968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92542","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>Between 1 April 2010 and 31 March 2014, the Environment Agency spent £4,370,000 on flood alleviation in Shropshire. This figure can only be split over financial years as follows:</p><p><br><br></p><p><strong>2010/11 </strong>£2,868,000</p><p> </p><p><strong>2011/12 </strong>£493,000</p><p> </p><p><strong>2012/13 </strong>£526,000</p><p> </p><p><strong>2013/14 </strong>£483,000</p><p> </p><p>These figures include capital, revenue maintenance and the Government recovery expenditure following the winter of 2013/14.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92542/answer",,,,,,"2014-10-17T11:12:13.06151Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92542/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92542/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Floods: Shropshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much the Environment Agency spent on flood defence measures in Shropshire in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012 and (d) 2013.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","209959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92543","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-17","<p>The Government does not keep estimated numbers of cats nor any breakdown of the type requested. However, according to the Pet Food Manufacturers’ Association’s Pet Population report of 2014 there are an estimated 8 million domestic cats in this country. The corresponding reports for the four previous years gave the following estimates: 2013 – 8.5 million; 2012 – 8 million; 2011 – 8 million; 2010 – 8 million.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92543/answer",,,,,"209969 ; 209970","2014-10-17T11:14:10.0975849Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92543/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92543/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-10","Cats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the proportion of the cat population which has been neutered in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","Thirsk and Malton","Miss Anne McIntosh","209967"
